(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Bona Mugabe, who has just been named to Zimbabwe's unpopular censorship board, knows what it's like to be gossiped about.News24 CorrespondentHarare - A buffalo that killed a woman in western Zimbabwe had likely been wounded by a poacher first, the state wildlife authority said on Saturday.Olivia Ndlovu, 68, was attacked by the buffalo in Tsholotsho district on Monday as she tried to bring in her cattle, according to a statement from the Zimbabwe Parks and Wildlife Management Authority. She died in hospital on Wednesday, before she had received any treatment for the broken arm, leg and ribs she sustained during the attack.Wounded buffaloes are among the most dangerous animals in the world. The Cape buffalo, which is present in Zimbabwe, is known as the "widow-maker" because of its fearsome reputation.The buffalo was killed by rangers on Wednesday - but not before it had time to attack and injure a 4-year-old girl. She is currently in hospital with a fractured leg in Tsholotsho.The parks authority's spokesperson Caroline Washaya-Moyo said the buffalo had spear wounds "hence the violent behaviour." 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.